                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d568">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1162/7: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Canton</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Jenkins</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-04-03T14:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 3, 1926—2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your telegram to the Legation, March 23, 1 p.m. The Associated Press has reported
                    from Hongkong that the Kweilin rioting was a Communist movement against American
                    missionaries, and it informally asks if this and other incidents, such as the
                    picketing of the hospital at Canton, are a part merely of a general antiforeign
                    feeling or are evidences that there is a special hostility against Americans.
                    Has there been at Kweilin no molestation of missionaries of other nationality
                    than American?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
